<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1311,1950]" pageId="2" pageNumber="221">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,564,1347,1374]" pageId="2" pageNumber="221">Description and identification.</emphasis>
Forewing length: 
<quantity box="[772,875,1347,1374]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.64" pageId="2" pageNumber="221" unit="mm" value="16.4">16.4 mm</quantity>
. Wingspan: 
<quantity box="[1014,1114,1348,1374]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.07" pageId="2" pageNumber="221" unit="mm" value="30.7">30.7 mm</quantity>
. General appearence similar to that of female with bright red-orange upperside with black border on both wings and paler yellow underside. Forewing black border, hindwing marginal band slightly broader than in female, hindwing band tapers down to narrow black marginal line, terminates at tornus. Both sexes of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schultze" baseAuthorityYear="1917" box="[836,971,1455,1481]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Parasiomera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="221" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paradoxa">
<emphasis box="[836,971,1455,1481]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="221">P. paradoxa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have broader black border on the wings, and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Stempffer, 1962)" baseAuthorityName="Stempffer" baseAuthorityYear="1962" box="[197,534,1491,1518]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Parasiomera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="221" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orientalis">
<emphasis box="[197,331,1491,1517]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="221">P. orientalis</emphasis>
(Stempffer, 1962)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Safian &amp; Collins, 2015" authorityName="Safian &amp; Collins" authorityYear="2015" box="[586,975,1491,1518]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Parasiomera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="221" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kivuensis">
<emphasis box="[586,715,1491,1517]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="221">P. kivuensis</emphasis>
Sáfián &amp; Collins, 2015
</taxonomicName>
have a tiny black dot at the end of the cell on the forewing underside (Sáfián &amp; Collins 2015). The genitalia of the specimen illustrated in 
<figureCitation box="[1217,1282,1527,1554]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1146,1170]" captionTargetBox="[157,1432,186,1116]" captionTargetId="figure-16@3.[151,1436,181,1122]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Known localities of Parasiomera alfa." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4403024" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4403024/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="221">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
are similar to those of all other species in the genus, showing slight differences from those of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schultze" baseAuthorityYear="1917" box="[1046,1181,1563,1589]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Parasiomera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="221" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paradoxa">
<emphasis box="[1046,1181,1563,1589]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="221">P. paradoxa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: the uncus in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Safian" authorityYear="2015" box="[1339,1411,1563,1589]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Parasiomera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="221" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alfa">
<emphasis box="[1339,1411,1563,1589]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="221">P. alfa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is more slender and its pointed tip is longer, similarly their sacci (this should be viewed in proportion, as the examined male of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Safian" authorityYear="2015" box="[243,314,1635,1661]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Parasiomera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="221" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alfa">
<emphasis box="[243,314,1635,1661]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="221">P. alfa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is larger than the comparative specimen of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schultze" baseAuthorityYear="1917" box="[803,938,1635,1661]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Parasiomera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="221" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paradoxa">
<emphasis box="[803,938,1635,1661]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="221">P. paradoxa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1311,1950]" pageId="2" pageNumber="221">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,355,1672,1698]" pageId="2" pageNumber="221">New records.</emphasis>
The species was described from the unique female 
<typeStatus box="[923,1025,1671,1697]" pageId="2" pageNumber="221">holotype</typeStatus>
. It was collected on a hilltop, circling rather low with a male which escaped. Very similar bright-orange specimens have since been observed in the Putu Range, the Foya Proposed Protected Area and in the Wologizi Mountains, displaying high up under the canopy of tall ant-trees usually on hilltops. These displaying males did not descend to ground level, and could not be caught, and therefore the true identity of them could not be confirmed. However, a single male was captured under similar circumstance with a long-handle net on a hilltop in the Wologizi Mountains, which supports the possibility of a species more widely distributed in lowland forests in the Liberian sub-region. Only the confirmed new record is listed here and the specimen is illustrated on 
<figureCitation box="[587,654,1923,1950]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1945,1969]" captionTargetBox="[182,1408,561,1909]" captionTargetId="figure-62@1.[170,1417,550,1921]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Parasiomera imagos: P. alfa male (Liberia, Wologizi Mountains) upperside—A, underside—B; P. paradoxa male (Cameroon, Ebogo) upperside—C, underside—D; P. paradoxa (lectotype female (Cameroon, Yendi, Southwest Region) upperside—E, underside—F." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4403019" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4403019/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="221">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
